---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import CaseSelector from '../components/CaseSelector.tsx';
import SimplifiedInputs from '../components/SimplifiedInputs.tsx';
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
---

<BaseLayout title="Step 2: Select" step={2} prev={`${base}1-discover/`} next={`${base}3-qualify/`}>
  <div class="max-w-5xl mx-auto py-10 px-4 landing-content">

    <div class="mb-10">
      <h1>Select a workflow</h1>
      <p class="subtitle">Pick a workflow to work through the rest of the guide with.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="mb-10">
      <h2>Picking the right one</h2>

      <p>
        After discovery, you will usually have a list of candidate workflows. The temptation is to pick the one that feels most urgent or the one leadership is most excited about. But the best workflow to evaluate first is not necessarily the most important one. It is the one where you can run a clean, bounded pilot and learn the most. The next step will help you check this formally, but use your instinct here.
      </p>

      <p>
        If you have your own workflow in mind, describe it below. That is the main goal of this step. If you want to see how the guide works first, pick one of the four built-in scenarios. They come with pre-filled data so you can click through immediately.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="divider"></div>

    <div class="mb-10">
      <CaseSelector client:load />

      <p style="margin-top: 1.5rem; color: var(--text-light);">
        Once you have picked or described a workflow, the next step checks whether it is ready to pilot.
      </p>

      <div class="divider"></div>

      <div class="mb-10">
        <h2>About your setup</h2>
        <SimplifiedInputs client:load section="context" />
      </div>
    </div>

  </div>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .landing-content .subtitle {
    color: var(--text-light);
    font-size: 15px;
  }
</style>
